\par }\pard\plain \s15\qj\nowidctlpar\adjustright \lang2057 {<#/>Nearly seven million Kenyans will be jobless by the turn of the century unless the growth of the labour force is ch
ecked. <#/>Unemployment is undesirable. <#/>It has bad effects on an individual, not to mention the community.
\par }\pard\plain \qj\nowidctlpar\adjustright \fs20\lang1031 {<#/>}{\fs24\lang2057 Joblessness leads to hunger and poverty. <#/>Some of the jobless may resort to such social evils as prostitution, drug abuse, thuggery and other criminal activities.
\par <#/>Kenya, like any other developing country, suffers from the problem of unemployment and underemployment.
\par <#/>Unemployment is a state of not being able to have a source of income despite one's skills. <#/>The problem is basically one of lack of access to income-earning opportunities.
\par <#/>It follows that many people who are otherwise considered to be employed, but whose productivity, output and incomes are unacceptably low, should in fact be considered as unemployed.
\par <#/>Every year
, more than 600,000 Kenyans enter the labour market. <#/>Over 90 per cent of these are young school leavers and college graduates of ages 15 to 20. <#/>Only 10 per cent of these get the 63,000 jobs created each year in the modern wage sector.
\par <#/>Kenya's t
otal labour force is approaching ten million. <#/>About 1.4 million are employed in the wage sector. <#/>Manufacturing absorbs over 290,000 and services about 670,000. <#/>The balance from the 1.4 million is absorbed in construction and other specialised 
sectors.
\par <#/>Three quarters of the 10 million labour force work in the rural non-wage sector mostly as peasant farmers. <#/>This is why agriculture is considered the most important employer.
\par <#/>A smaller number about 350,000 is employed in small enterprises, while urban informal (<ea/>jua <ea/>kali) employs about 450,000 workers. <#/>Another 50,000 are "unpaid" family workers.
\par <#/>Official statistics on Kenya's unemployment or underemployment are not published but some economists say that the unemployment r
ate ranges between 15 and 20 per cent. <#/>If those underemployed are included then this rate could be 30 per cent. <#/>These percentages are, however, disputed by the treasury which holds a conservative 12 per cent unemployed rate figure.
\par <#/>The rate at which jobs are being created continues to lag behind }{\b\v\fs24\lang2057 <+_the>}{\v\fs24\lang2057  }{\fs24\lang2057 fast expanding labour force. <#/>The private sector which employs slightly under half of }{\b\v\fs24\lang2057 <+_the>}{
\v\fs24\lang2057  }{\fs24\lang2057 total modern wages sector workers has in the past five years experienced a slow growth of about three per cent compared to the public sector's 42 per cent.
\par }\pard\plain \s15\qj\nowidctlpar\adjustright \lang2057 {<#/>The most promising sector is self employment including informal sector activities and small enterprises especially for professional young graduates. <#/>Self employment and informal sector emplo
yment has been expanding at a rate of over 10 per cent annually in the last five years. <#/>Since the government will not be a major source of employment creation because of budgetary constraints, it is expected that small-scale enterprises owned by eithe
r professionals (lawyers, doctors, engineers, etc.) or <ea/>jua <ea/>kali artisans will be the major source of employment.
\par }\pard\plain \qj\nowidctlpar\adjustright \fs20\lang1031 {<#/>}{\fs24\lang2057 But recent events by local government in particular the City Commission have cast doubts about the sector's (<ea/>jua <ea/>kali) continued expansion.
\par <#/>The eviction of hawkers from their places of work, demolition of kiosks in the last several months have left Kenyans wondering what the Commission was up to.
\par <#/>Informal sectors are basically non-structural <-_economic><+_economy> oriented in nature, characterised by low capitalisation, simple technology, labour intensive }{\b\v\fs24\lang2057 <&/>grammar}{\fs24\lang2057  and availability of raw materials.

\par <#/>Some <-_example><+_examples> of these are maize roasters, shoe shiners, kiosks wood-carvings and many others which can be seen as valuable modes of helping to reduce the hazards of increased unemployment.
\par <#/>There are 1,613,000 Kenyans in wage employment in the country and by the year 2000, Kenya's modern wage employment will have increased to between 2,060,000 and 2,330,000.
\par <#/>The number of people in the urban informal sector will rise to between 350,000 and 400,000 and rural non-farm activities will rise between 2,250,000 and 2,840,000.
\par <#/>The above figures show that unemployment in the country has reached alarming proportions. <#/>The ranks of the unemployed swell every year as students leave schools and universities.
\par <#/>Under-employment is a permanent characteristic of Africa while the African university "has become a factory for turning out skills which are not needed by employers."
\par Today, paper qualifications in the form of a degree, a diploma or a certificate are not tickets to jobs.
\par <#/>The first comprehensive study of Kenya's unem
ployment problem was carried out in 1970 by a select committee of the National Assembly. <#/>Two years' later, the problem was given further scrutiny by the International Labour Organisation's (ILO) mission to Kenya.
\par <#/>In 1983 President Moi appointed a Presidential Committee on Unemployment under the chairmanship of Mr Maina Wanjigi. <#/>Following the presentation of the report, the government published Sessional Paper No. 2 of 1985 on unemployment.
\par <#/>The Wanjigi committee was appointed to examine the problem of unemployment and recommend both short and long-term strategies for its alleviation.
\par <#/>Specifically the committee was required to consider and recommend measures which would stimulate growth both in public and private sectors, disperse employment opportunities to areas of greatest need, promote labour-intensive methods of production.

\par <#/>Other areas the committee was expected to look into was the reduction of the labour force and its migration to urban areas, the need to improve the relevance of training and education with a view to alleviating the school-leaver problem.
\par <#/>The committee was further required to examine the probabilities of initiating and expanding programmes with a high employment content and at low cost and to suggest measures w
hich would enhance the contribution of public and private sector institutions to employment creation.
\par <#/>The committee completed its work and presented its report to President Moi in May 1983.
