\par }{\fs24\lang2057 <h>}{\b\fs24\lang2057  }{\fs24 <#/>}{\b\fs24\lang2057 Legal rights of civil servants }{\fs24\lang2057 </h>}{\b\fs24\lang2057 
\par }{<#/>}{\fs24\lang2057 Now and then cases of harassment of civil servants at their place of work come to light. <#/>Unreasonable or unjustified dismissals are not uncommon. <#/>In most of these cases, no recourse 
is made to legal remedy as there seems to be a belief, an incorrect one at that, that the government cannot be, questioned on how it treats its civil servants.
\par <#/>As our civil service, or at least its foundations, was established by the British, it is worthwhile to be familiar with the status of civil servants under the English legal system.
\par <#/>At common law civil servants have no security of tenure and they can be dismissed at any time by the Crown without notice. <#/>This applies even if it was agreed at the time of appointment that the civil servant would be employed for a fixed term.

\par <X_>}{\v\fs24\lang2057 <#/>The com
mon law position of civil servants in England has, however, been significantly altered by legislation over the years. The Employment Protection (Consolidation) Act 1978 applies to the Crown (subject to certain limitations) and this gives civil servants th
e right not to be unfairly dismissed. The most important exception concerns national security.
\par Under the Act, an employee who considers that he has been unfairly dismissed can bring proceedings before an industrial tribunal, which may order reinstatement or
 award compensation. These rights, which were originally granted by the Industrial Relations Act 1971, to a large extent - though not entirely - remove the common law disabilities of civil servants. And even where a civil servant has no common law protect
ion against dismissal, it does not necessarily follow that he has no legal rights to the salary he has earned by work already done.
\par Until the Superannuation Act 1972 came into force a civil servant in England had no legal right to his pension and the final 
decision always rested with the Treasury. Now, however, the 1972 Act makes provision for the determination by the courts of questions of law - though it is still possible for the minister to provide that questions of fact will be decided by himself.

\par In Ken
ya, the common law position obtains although there is nevertheless scope for legal redress in the courts, for example when the salary of a civil servant is withheld without justification or where dismissal has been effected <-_is><+_in> breach of the laid
 down administrative and statutory procedures.
\par }\pard\plain \s15\qj\nowidctlpar\adjustright \lang2057 {\v 
The power of appointment of civil servants is divided between the President, the Public Service Commission in whom certain powers are vested by the Constitution, and Permanent Secretaries and heads of departmen
ts to whom certain powers have been delegated. The President appoints the Commission itself, all Permanent Secretaries and other named officials. The Commission appoints the administrative and professional classes, and the higher grades of secretarial, ex
ecutive and technical classes. Permanent Secretaries and others have delegated to them the power to appoint and exercise general administration over the lower grades of the last three classes, and the subordinate staff.
\par }\pard\plain \qj\nowidctlpar\adjustright \fs20\lang1031 {\v\fs24\lang2057 The powers of discipline and compulso
ry retirement are shared between the Public Service Commission and senior servants - usually heads of departments - to whom the Commission has delegated its powers, and in <-/relion> to teachers, a specialised branch of the public service, the Teachers Se
rvice Commission. Disciplinary procedures <-/varh> from reprimand to dismissal or termination of appointment.
\par With the dissolution of the Kenya Civil Servants Union, some years ago the present administrative and statutory protection for the low-cadre civil servant does not seem adequate as witnessed by various grievances which have emerged in the public arena.

\par In May 1990, a clerk with the Ministry of Livestock Development struggled to present his problems to Kenya's Head of State, President Moi, during a ra
lly at Kakamega's Bukhungu Stadium. Mr David Mukhaye wanted to present his problems to the President because "the Head of State is always mindful of other people's welfare."
\par President Moi ordered the security officers who were struggling with Mr Mukhaye, to let him through and his complaints were later handed over to a Permanent Secretary in the Office of the President in-charge of internal security, Mr Hezekiah Oyugi.
\par Mukhaye later narrated to the press the circumstances which forced him to take this step.
 He said he had not received <-/hi> salary since April 1989, when he was sent on forced leave by the ministry officials. He said he was undergoing mental torture because he had no funds to support his family and other dependants.
\par The distraught civil serva
nt explained that his two brothers and two sisters were unable to continue with their education because of lack of funds. He <-/sai> his landlord was threatening to evict him from the house, for which he was paying Shs 100 per month, because he had defaul
ted for eight months.
\par Mukhaye, attached to his ministry's Western Provincial offices in Kakamega, complained that he had written two letters to his Permanent Secretary, asking for an explanation over his forced leave, but had not received any reply. It is n
ot known how the matter ended after it had been placed in the hands of Mr Oyugi.
\par In a situation whereby junior civil servants, subordinate staff belonged to a trade union, such a situation would not have arisen. The reasons given for disbanding the trade u
nion for junior civil servants and subordinate staff were never clear, least of all convincing, and indeed contravened the international standards of trade unionism as set out by the International Labour Organisation. The Office of Ombudsman, if ever esta
blished, will also serve as a check against bureaucratic insensitivity.
\par What about the big guns, that is those high up there in the civil service and whose performance eschews public accountability? As the expression has it, who is to guard the guards? This
 is a matter which needs immediate attention for it is high time that the performance of senior officials became subject to some parliamentary control. If this were so, we would not be faced with the futility which, year in and year out, continues to meet
 the exhortations by the Public Accounts Committee for senior civil servants to control expenditure in their respective ministries. That recently telephone line }{\b\v\fs24\lang2057 <&/>grammar}{\v\fs24\lang2057 
 to various government ministries had to be cut, for nonpayment of accumulated pills, speaks very unfavourable }{\b\v\fs24\lang2057 <&/>grammar}{\v\fs24\lang2057 
 of the degree of financial management in our civil service. The other matter which needs some kind of parliamentary sanction in the area of misuse of power especially as these relate to actions which flagrantly violate the country's constitution.
\par We can take a leaf out of the American experience. For much of the Supreme Court's early history, it flirted with the erroneous belief that the President had the sole power to remove inferior officers.
\par It is not as if the constitution is completely silent on removal; to the contrary, one of the impeachment clauses specifically provides for the removal of "all civil officers."
\par Congressional authority to affect appointive offices, in effect to exercise its own tenure prerogative, gained full recognition in the last quarter of the nineteenth century.
\par The democratic nightmare of Watergate, the Iran-Contra affair, and the allegations against former Attorney General Meese underscore the significance of the problem which faces the gover
ned everywhere: Who is to investigate those citizens who are believed to be above suspicion? The Watergate reality includes jail time done by former cabinet members and key presidential advisers. Only the unresolved questions of constitutionality prevente
d the grand jury from indicting Richard Nixon himself.
\par It is a sad realisation that the muck which is <-/beleaguring> our civil service by way of corruption was virtually absent in the high echelons of the colonial civil service. The colonial civil service 
was manned by remarkable civil servants who wished to see the colony run efficiently and justly; this was a difficult task within the milieu of colonialism, but at least they tried to ward off the virus of corruption.
\par The song about pruning the public serv
ice of corrupt elements has today become a hackneyed affair; and so has been the song about the need of civil servants being " servants of the people rather than masters." It is high time that effective machinery of checks and balances were established an
d whereby safeguarded tenure of office would be meaningful.}{\fs24\lang2057 </X>
