\par }{\fs24\lang2057 <I>}{\b\fs24\lang2057  }{\fs24\lang2057 <h>}{\b\fs24\lang2057  }{\fs24 <#/>}{\b\fs24\lang2057 Varsities expansion yet to meet demand }{\fs24\lang2057 </h>}{\b\fs24\lang2057 
\par }{\fs24\lang2057 <h>}{\b\fs24\lang2057  }{\fs24 <#/>}{\b\fs24\lang2057 Only seven per cent of the candidates were admitted }{\fs24\lang2057 <h>}{\b\fs24\lang2057 
\par }{<#/>}{\fs24\lang2057 With 40,000 students in local universities and another 15,000 studying overseas, many people think we have too many people taking degrees.
\par <#/>The crunch came last year when the State universities had a double intake of 20,000 undergraduates, about a third of them taking education.
\par <#/>This followed the 1987 double intake of 10,000 students.
\par <#/>This year's intake of 10,000 students will just add on to an explosive situation, critics argue.
\par <#/>But are we really producing too many university graduates? <#/>
\par The number admitted this year only presented 7.5 per cent of the 133,063 of the Kenya Certificate of Secondary Education (KCSE) candidates which still makes university education elitist, contrary to what critics say.
\par <#/>The problem is compounded when one considers that all the candidates who have scored a C plain in KCSE - about 40,000 \- are actually university material.
\par <#/>So, we are far from producing too many graduates when the problem is looked into from that perspective.
\par <#/>But compared to other African countries, Kenya has one of the highest university enrolment.
\par <#/>Uganda has only 5,000 students in the once famous Makerere University while Tanzania has the same number at Dar es Salaam and Sokoine universities.
\par <#/>However, when most people talk about over-production of graduates, they have the problem of unemployed graduates in mind.
\par <#/>The job opportunities for graduates have been dwindling which, to the layman, is a manifestation that there are too many graduates around.
\par <#/>To the laymen, university education is supposed to be a ticket to a good job due to the skills it gives its holder.
\par <#/>However, unemployed graduates is also a reflection that the economy cannot support the number of graduates being produced by our universities and other tertiary institutions.
\par <#/>That is the critical issue that educational planners have to address themselves to.
\par <#/>They have to decide whether universities enrolment should be pegged to employment opportunities available or not.
\par <#/>University dons would dread an admission policy that pegs admission to job opportunities for it would reduce universities to mere training institutions.
\par <X_>}{\v\fs24\lang2057 <#/>The job of university scholars is not merely to teach. They are supposed to discover new knowledge through research.
\par However, some economists would advocate that unless faculties are meeting the needs of the job market, their expansion should be curbed.
\par British universities felt the pinch of such policies under Margaret Thatcher when faculties which offered few employment opportunities faced closure due to financial cutbacks.
\par If such rules were followed, enrolment in arts and science faculties would be severely reduced as it is their graduates who face most acute unemployment problem.
\par But in so doing, the universities would lose faculties which played a vital role in supporting the so-called professional courses like medicine and engineering.
\par Science faculties in particular are indispensable as they support the technical faculties.
\par But the faculties of arts and science need to be trimmed to manageable proportions instead of being the dumping ground for those who failed to enter professional courses.
\par The unemployment of graduates and diploma holders is reaching alarming proportions.
\par The case of agriculture graduates and veterinary medicine who for the last two years could not get jobs is already known.
\par However, unemployment is also affecting engineering students although the exact number of the unemployed graduate engineers is unknown.
\par }\pard\plain \s15\qj\nowidctlpar\adjustright \lang2057 {\v Also affected are the diploma holders from agricultural institutions like Egerton University, Embu, Bukura and others.
\par }\pard\plain \qj\nowidctlpar\adjustright \fs20\lang1031 {\v\fs24\lang2057 Many graduates of national polytechnics who had not been sponsored by an employer are still unemployed.
\par Even the Kenya Technical Teachers College graduates who took courses like mechanical and electrical engineering cannot get jobs as few schools are offering such courses.
\par But does this mean we stop expanding higher education? Far from it.
\par Higher education cannot be viewed from the context of immediate employment as it has other invisible benefits that contribute to national development.
\par An educated population is a national asset as it attracts investors who love countries with cheap and skilled labour. An educated person has better chances of being self-employed.
\par Informed citizenry is also more innovative than an uneducated one and so it is in a better position to solve some of the country's social and economic problems leading to unemployment. An educated labour force is capable of adapting to
 modern technologies and thus becomes more productive and efficient. Even elementary education has proved to enhance agricultural production, studies by the World Bank have shown. The success of newly industrialised countries of South East Asia - Korea, S
ingapore, Taiwan and <-/Hong-kong> - owe their achievement to their heavy investment in the right education.
\par Kenya may want to know that in 1960 Korea was actually poorer than Kenya. But the former made the economic breakthrough despite lacking major natura
l resources due to its industrious and well educated population when we have yet to cross the valley of poverty.
\par The critical issue in the development of university education in Kenya is uncontrolled expansion of the soft-option arts courses.
\par The Director of Education, Prof James Waithaka, recently said that out of the 40,000 students enrolled only 14,800 or 37 per cent of them were taking science-based courses.
\par The registrar of Kenyatta University,
\par Prof S.N. Bogonko, said the universities have been producing too many arts graduates largely due to lack of funds to expand the scientific and technical courses which required expensive equipment.
\par It is important to note that even with the double intake, the universities still produced only 100 doctors every year due to lack of training facilities.
\par All the same, we are in a vicious circle. The country cannot solve its economic problems without skilled manpower. But that manpower cannot get jobs unless the economy is growing.
\par When that circle is broken, we shall be on the right track of economic development.}{\fs24\lang2057 </X>
